english:
  title: In Praise of Bodhidharma's Portrait
  author: Lee Kyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At Shaolin, facing the wall—
    it was the mind he sought to transmit.
    The mind is already passed to the Eastern lands;
    the body shall depart westward with form.

    In this present moment,
    what can be transmitted is mind;
    what is useless is the body.
    The body has already gone—
    why then must we paint his likeness?

    To paint a portrait seeking the mind
    is like searching for pearls in a serpent's shed skin.
    Body or portrait—
    which exists, which does not?
    The body is an object within a dream;
    the portrait, a dream within a dream.

    Vague and nebulous, all dissolving into depths,
    everything returns to nothingness.
    Only the mind remains,
    enduring forever alongside the moon.
  footnotes:
    - Bodhidharma (Daruma in Japanese, Damo in Chinese) was the legendary founder of Chan/Zen Buddhism who is said to have meditated facing a wall at Shaolin Temple for nine years.
    - The reference to 'Eastern lands' (震旦, Zhendan) reflects the Buddhist perspective of transmission from India through China to Korea.
    - The 'moon' serves as a traditional poetic symbol for enlightenment and the eternal nature of consciousness in East Asian Buddhist poetry.
